Program3: reads a string and outputs a string. But in the chain, the output of program1 is an integer and is the input for program2. The output of program2 is a string and is the input for program3. However, the input for program3 is not the same as the output of program2? The problem does not specify that the programs are connected in a meaningful way. It just says: the output of each program is used as the input to the next. So we have to simulate exactly:

        Step1: Read two integers (a, b) -> then run program1 -> output an integer (say, X). Step2: Use X as the input for program2 -> program2 produces a string (say, S) of length X.

        Step3: Use S as the input for program3 -> program3 produces a string (T). Step4: Output T.

   We don't care if the output of program2 is not what program3 expects? We are just simulating the chain. However, note the behavior of program3: it expects a string of '.' and '-' but we are giving it a string of letters. How does it behave? The program3 code:

            for (int i = 0; i < n.length; i++) {
                if (n[i] == '.') {
                    if (s) {
                        System.out.print(1);
                        s = false;
                    } else {
                        System.out.print(0);
                    }
                } else {
                    if (s) {
                        System.out.print(2);
                        s = false;
                    } else {
                        s = true;
                    }
                }
            } In the else branch: when the character is not '.', which in our case is a letter (so always not '.'), then:

            if s is true -> output 2 and set s to false.
            else -> set s to true. And note: s is a boolean that is initially false. So for each character:

            First character (if not '.'): 
                s is false -> set s to true (and output nothing for this character). Second character (if not '.'): 
                s is true -> output 2 and set s to false. Then next character: set s to true (output nothing) and then if next is not '.' and s is true -> output 2.
